    Peter S. says:
    April 17, 2013 at 12:22 am

    Are we intending to discuss pure ontology? I can rant reductivistly for a good while about ‚Äúthe map is not the territory‚Äù, about all perceptions being extremely likely bets against reality and not guarantees, about the problems inherent in the ‚Äúis of identity‚Äù, etc. and thus really start building from the ground up, but I don‚Äôt know if that‚Äôd be overshooting the mark, maybe.

    To me, if we‚Äôre defining a reductivist calculus, game = toy + rule. A toy is anything we decide to treat as a toy: it‚Äôs a purely arbitrary designation and (critically) not intrinsic in the item. A rule is anything that defines the mental space in which the toy is interacted with; anything that separates the field of all possible actions in any arbitrary way. A child playing catch with themselves has decided an object that can be thrown is now a toy (hopefully not the cat), and has decided catching is better than not-catching and likely also that a higher throw is better than a less-high throw.

    (In this context we are not limiting ‚Äútoy‚Äù to physical object, either, but literally ANYTHING, ‚Äúarbitrary‚Äù in the strict sense, nor do the rules have any constraint: ‚Äúall rules must make sense‚Äù and ‚Äúno rules shall contradict each other‚Äù are also rules, and not required. But physical objects and sensible rules are easier to make parsable examples out of.)

    The subset of possible games we are interested in (games we create for others to play) are all forms of communication, and at its (reductivist) core communication is inducing an experience in another. We can go down the rabbit hole of communication theory too, if we like, to establish that boundary, but at least we‚Äôd be able to resolve the idea that certain kinds of induced experiences (or attempts at inducing certain kinds of experiences) are mutually exclusive to the idea of games. (It also helps with the ‚Äúare games art‚Äù question, but only by negation: paintings versus paint, basically, the message is not the medium, and art is the communication not the channel, in this context.)

    I mean, there‚Äôs a lot of reinventing the wheel we don‚Äôt really need to do, but I‚Äôm also not really the best person to not-do it. üôÇ
