    Raph says:
    April 17, 2013 at 9:48 pm

    Kylotan,

    I really don‚Äôt think that‚Äôs the case.

    Game IS overloaded even from a formal perspective. If we take a game grammar version of ‚Äúgame,‚Äù the following genres already don‚Äôt fit:

    Interactive fiction, adventure games, Heavy Rain-style spaces, any MMO that is more than a pure hack n slash (which isn‚Äôt any of them, these days), Cut the Rope and maybe Angry Birds (debatable), Professor Layton‚Ä¶

    Yes, there‚Äôs certainly broad similarities. But really, to get somewhere with formalism, as Keith points out, we need to get tighter, and if anything, a formal version of the term is likely to get narrower.

    This isn‚Äôt counting the many casual uses of the term that are in the language, such as ‚Äúplaying games with someone‚Äôs feelings‚Äù and so on.

    Secondly, I DO think there is value in incorporating things like reader response theory into the formalism. As all of us formalists have been saying for a long time, we‚Äôre essentially really working with the canvas of the mind when we work with game systems. Acknowledging that the formal construct we have been calling ‚Äúgame‚Äù is one that exists in the player‚Äôs head fairly independently of the artifact is important, and not very different really from the types of rules that Salen & ZImmerman described in Rules of Play.

    Essentially, we have been saying that game grammar is about constituative rules, the ones that the game defines; but in practice, since players often build the rulesets in their heads as they play, we‚Äôre doing ourselves a disservice by not looking at the ‚Äúconstituative rules‚Äù of the actual game they are playing as opposed to the one we construct as designers. Phrased differently, I am saying that game grammar can probably be applied to game dynamics. That‚Äôs a big deal.

    Finally, I wouold go further, and say that this lets us use the tools we have developed in game grammar and similar efforts and apply them to things we have historically set outside of game. This change in mindset says we can do something like analyze ‚Äúplaying the stock market‚Äù using the same grammar we use to analyze chess. That has real value, and may help deal with the excesses and fallacies of gamification.

    FWIW, nothing in the essay is new thinking as of this week. You can see most of this in the Ten Years Later talk, and there are echoes of it in Ernest Adams‚Äô definition of game, in Will Wright‚Äôs talks, and other sources. I wrote it all out simply because a) there are some on the formalist side who perhaps do not focus enough on this mental model process, and b) there are many on the reader response side who think we don‚Äôt EVER think about games as process.
