    Bob Moore says:
    April 18, 2013 at 9:21 am

    Hey Raph,

    You draw attention to ‚Äúsystem‚Äù and to ‚Äúattitude,‚Äù but one thing I think is missing here is ‚Äúsocial action‚Äù or ‚Äúpractice.‚Äù It‚Äôs not just that an individual perceives a particular system as a game but that he or she TREATS it as such. That is, people DO ‚Äúplaying chess‚Äù or DO ‚Äúplaying Snakes and Ladders.‚Äù These shared practices are recognizable to competent others. And it is these shared forms of action, social practices, or ‚Äúlanguage games‚Äù (for Wittgenstein), that keep us out of the ‚Äúsoup of subjectivity.‚Äù

    If you‚Äôre doing ‚Äúplaying chess,‚Äù then you are treating the situation ‚Äì board, pieces and other person ‚Äì as ‚Äúthe game of chess‚Äù whether you‚Äôre having fun or not. If you start improvising on that practice (I once created an RPG-style game that uses a chess board and pieces), you‚Äôre doing something other than ‚Äúplaying chess.‚Äù Or if you‚Äôre ‚Äúbuilding‚Äù a chess set or ‚Äúselling‚Äù one, you‚Äôre doing things with the artifacts and perhaps another person that are NOT enacting the game.

    Furthermore, the rules of a game ultimately define the ‚Äúsystem‚Äù of a game, but the system is more than the rules. The rules are features of the shared practice. They are resources for talking about gameplay, justifying moves, sanctioning opponents, teaching correct practice and more. But any articulation of the rules is always an incomplete representation of that practice itself. Consequently, the best way to learn to play is to observe the practice rather than simply to read a formulation of the rules.

    So I‚Äôd say it‚Äôs not individuals‚Äô attitudes toward situations that make them ‚Äúgames,‚Äù but rather the form of individuals‚Äô actions in those situations and their relation to shared ways of playing.
    kylotan says:
    April 18, 2013 at 9:41 am

    @Peter S.
    I think that‚Äôs a very interesting point. But I would simply say that ‚Äúemergent play‚Äù is not necessarily ‚Äúgameplay‚Äù. Designing for emergent play is getting into the realm of meta game design, or to put it in more classic terms, toy design. ie. How can we make an artifact that facilitates or encourages play? Some of those forms of play may turn out to be games, and some may not. It‚Äôs a useful concept for developers, but I feel it‚Äôs one that builds upon ‚Äòpure‚Äô game design, whatever that is, rather than being an integral part of it. Emergent play doesn‚Äôt require that a game emerges from it, nor do games have to emerge from an artifact, so the 2 concepts stand alone.

    Hence, sandboxes aren‚Äôt really games in my personal view, but there are certainly virtual worlds which function as both game and as sandbox, each side having closely-related but distinct traits.
