    Looking for controversies in brain sciences these days is ‚Äúlike handing out speeding tickets at the Indy 500‚Äù but, arguably, the biggest current controversy, in all of neuroscience, is how that all-of-neuroscience is being conducted. It‚Äôs crazy time! Meta-analysis studies have been showing all kinds of poor practice from statistical incompetence, bias, and methodological sloppiness, you name it. Add to this, the fact that anything that gets to popular media is usually so distorted and warped by the press-release-to-reporting-to-editing cycle that what the headline reads typically looks nothing like the original work‚Äîwild claims and speculations abound. That ‚Äúneurobollocks‚Äù I mentioned above, the biggest hucksters of it come from the fields of psychology.

    In the games field, we are also often guilty of enthusiastic, misguided noise. As an entertainment field it seems less important that we‚Äôre upright. I believe that view is wrong. A few weeks ago, for example, I heard someone had claimed games were ‚Äúmore effective than morphine.‚Äù Which, I‚Äôm kind about it, is irresponsible. I‚Äôve been to the UW HIT Lab to visit Hunter Hoffman, I‚Äôve worn the helmet and played Snow World; I‚Äôm reasonable familiar with it. The treatment is more effective than morphine ALONE. But the treatment involves patients playing the VR game, Snow World, while ALSO on morphine. The awesomeness is that the dose that they require is lower. And, most importantly, while the effects of morphine on its own attenuate‚Äîpatients need more and more over time‚Äîthe effects of the VR game don‚Äôt! ‚ÄúNew therapies using games work better than drugs alone‚Äù is an amazing, important story, and we do harm by misrepresenting it. (Incidentally, as a game designer, you‚Äôll probably appreciate the challenges in designing for that kind of application: consider that players are on narcotics, and likely unable to act in highly skilled ways. You have to adjust your usual design intuitions for special, lower-ability audiences!)

    It wasn‚Äôt until I came around to thinking of ATOF as ‚ÄúA Theory of a Kind of Fun,‚Äù working in a constrained scope, that I became accomodating towards it. I don‚Äôt describe it as an abstract model, but as a convenient analogy; a good introduction to a common sense view of a kind of experience without needing to be factual. I would love to take you up on the offer to assist the 2nd edition. I‚Äôve got suggestions, not complaints. üòÄ
